you should do some steps:

&lt;h2&gt;First way&lt;/h2&gt;
- use a `boolean` and name it as `SIGN`
 - change it&#39;s value each time you reach end of loop to determine sign based on 1 or 0 (true or false)
     - if `sign` was `true` use `+`
     - if `sign` was `false` use `-`

- increase `i` in for loop twice (`i+=2`) each time, so values of `i` will be `1, 3, 5, ...`
&lt;hr&gt;


    int n=10;int sum=0;int x=2;
    
    double d=0.00;
    boolean sign = true;
    for(int i=1; i&lt;=n ; i+=2 ){
    	d=Math.pow(x,i);
    	sum += ((sign)?(int)d:(-1*(int)d));
    	sign = !sign;
    }


&lt;h2&gt;Second way&lt;/h2&gt;

- use an `integer` and name it as `SIGN`
 - change it&#39;s value each time you reach end of loop to determine sign based on 1 or -1.
- since it has the same type as the iterator variable, you can define it in the loop.

&lt;hr&gt;



    int n=10;int sum=0;int x=2;
    
    for (int i = 1, sign = 1; i &lt;= n; i += 2, sign = -sign) {
    	sum += sign * (int)Math.pow(x, i);
    }

